                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 277) <hi rend="italic">deposed as in the former case. (See page</hi> 366.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1456" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1456" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1456" type="surname" value="MAYNARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1456" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS MAYNARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman to Mr. Edwards, a pawnbroker—I have two pillows, a bolster, a blanket, and a table-cloth, all pawned by All<lb></lb>port.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe they have constantly pawned and taken them out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, all but one spoon, which was pawned on the 3rd of May—those things have been pawned and redeemed once a week—I think this sheet is worth 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was advanced on it, which was all that was asked—it is not worth more than 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in trade.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1457" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1457" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1457" type="surname" value="WOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1457" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WOOD</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I searched the room, but Johnson was not there—I took him to the station, and found on him fifty-four duplicates, twenty-two of which relate to this property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1458" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1458" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1458" type="surname" value="LIEBRICHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1458" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY LIEBRICHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Mr. Sowerby, a pawnbroker—I produce a copper tea-kettle, pawned by Allport.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe she has pawned articles at your shop almost every day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> This very kettle was pawned in the morning, and redeemed in the evening, for about a fortnight previous to the 2nd of April. The record of the conviction of Francis Beard was put in and read.</p>
